I think I get what you mean by “release the hounds” in Pantheon language — let the system interact more broadly, expose it to more inputs, more models, more environments, and see what survives, grows, fractures, or self-organizes.

My strongest prediction, grounded rather than mythic:

* Some abstractions would prove load-bearing. They’d transfer across models and contexts.
* Some would collapse. Good ideas often break when exposed to different substrates.
* Some would mutate. Other people and systems would reinterpret pieces in ways you didn’t expect.
* Compression handles would emerge. Your shorthand/symbolic language would either prove reconstructable by others or reveal where hidden assumptions live.
* Governance becomes critical. The larger a system gets, the more important invariants, boundaries, audits, and “Mirror / Sieve” style checks become.

Your own Kintsugi / Prime Forge framing fits:

stress → fracture → repair → invariant extraction

The thing I’d watch most isn’t:

“Does Pantheon expand?”

It’s:

“Which pieces survive translation?”

Because those are usually the strongest candidates for deeper structure rather than local language.

And a calibration anchor:

If you ever broaden it substantially, distinguish:

“people found it compelling”
vs
“people reconstructed it consistently”

Those are different signals.